The bookkeeping system has enabled us to give our perturbation term 
the same structure as the interaction term of quantum electrodynamics 
(QED) with the constant  acting as a coupling constant. 
Therefore, the full apparatus of QED is available to analyze the 
effect of this term in a perturbation calculation. The result of such
an analysis is well-known and strongly suggests that a Dirac particle 
within our SO(3,2) model shows properties of an electrically charged 
particle. 
 
Let us come back to the separation of the quadratic terms in () 
from those that are linear in : 
Our perturbation term provides the exchange of momenta between two particles 
without changing the total momentum. Therefore, also the square of the
total momentum is conserved. This justifies the separation. It also adds to 
our understanding why it is possible to observe small terms (linear in ) 
in the presence of large terms (quadratic in ).

The standard formulation of QED introduces the interaction term by the
postulation of gauge invariance. The latter is achieved by adding a new
"gauge field" that couples to the electron field. Despite the great success 
of the gauge principle it does not really provide us with an insight into
the interaction process itself.
We, on the other hand, have explicitly constructed an interaction term from 
known elements of the electrons Fock space and also have defined the 
bookkeeping field in terms of these elements. This gives us a full
understanding of the mathematical and physical nature of this interaction
term.

Unlike the standard formulation, where the coupling constant enters as 
a free parameter that has to be determined by the experiment, our approach
does not leave room for any free parameter. This means that the coupling 
constant  is determined by the theory and, therefore, should be calculable.


ESTIMATE OF THE COUPLING CONSTANT 	 


This coupling constant is defined by the normalization of 
 in () relative to the  
operator  whose normalization is given by ().
This ratio can - in principle - be determined by correctly "counting" all 
contributions to () - in other words: by a careful analysis of the
volume element of the integral in (). 

More than 30 years ago A. Wyler discovered that the 
fine-structure constant  can be expressed by volumes of certain 
symmetric spaces. Being a mathematician he was not able to put his 
observation into a convincing physical context. 
Therefore, his work was criticized as fruitless numerology.  

Wyler's idea was picked up later by F. D. Smith, Jr. who extended 
Wyler's heuristic approach into a general scheme based on a 
fundamental Spin(8) symmetry. 
Smith was then able to express coupling constants and relations of particle 
masses by characteristic volumes with a remarkable degree of precision. 

Let us see how far our model will lead us and whether we possibly can find a 
physical explanation for these authors' observations. 

Consider the S-matrix element of electron-electron scattering (Moller 
scattering) (see e.g.). In the conventional formulation of QED this 
term involves two vertices and two -operators. 
The latter result in an intermediate photon. It defines those intermediate 
states that contribute to the calculation of the scattering amplitude.
In our formulation we have two -operators given by the
integral () instead. Whereas, by definition, there is one and only 
one  for each , the multiplicity of 
 with respect to  may be different.
Our task will be to determine the multiplicity of  
relative to  by "counting" the intermediate states that 
our approach allows for. 

We already have parameterized the contributions to the interaction term by 
the parameters  and . 
The way in which the parameters  are used in the perturbation calculation
defines the parameter space of  as (a subspace of) the euclidean . 
If we split off the -dependency we are left with the integral over 
and our task will be to determine the multiplicity, or the integration volume 
respectively, of the contributions with respect to . 

The basis for the evaluation of the integration volume is the particle 
momenta and the homogeneous Lorentz group acting on the particle momenta. 
The SO(3,1) acts transitively on a particles mass shell
  
The independent parameters  span a 3-dimensional parameter space. 
